{"type":"message","id":"16ef2d2d","parentId":"8c920841","timestamp":"2026-04-13T02:39:13.443Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There are many more usages of `map[string]string` throughout the file. The approach of globally replacing all occurrences is too broad. Let me revert and think of a different approach.\n\nThe real issue is that the `queryRequest.Params` is `map[string]string` but the `stock_kline` method passes numeric values.\n\nActually, there's a much simpler fix: since this is a Go issue with JSON unmarshaling, I could instead fix it by:\n1. Adding a custom JSON unmarshaler for queryRequest that converts all numeric params to strings\n2. Or, simply changing the Params field to `map[string]json.RawMessage` and then having the individual parse functions work differently\n\n\n3. Or, the simplest approach: make Params `map[string]any` and then have each method's case statement handle the type assertion\n\nBut looking at the actual code structure, most methods in the switch statement call helper functions that expect `map[string]string`. So I can't just change the type without updating all those call sites. Let me reconsider—maybe the cleanest solution is to keep Params as `map[string]string` but handle the type conversion differently, perhaps with a wrapper or custom unmarshaler.\n\nWait, actually the error is telling me that `req.Params` is being passed where a `map[string]string` is expected, which means there's already a mismatch between what the JSON unmarshaler produces and what the helper functions need.\n\nLet me try a different approach entirely—I'll define Params as `map[string]json.RawMessage` so the JSON can be unmarshaled without type conversion, then each method can parse its own params into the correct types. Alternatively, I could write a custom unmarshaler that converts numeric values to strings automatically during the unmarshal process, which would preserve backward compatibility with existing code that expects `map[string]string`. The helper functions already convert to string via `strconv.FormatUint`, so this approach might work cleanly.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully—I'm overcomplicating it. Let me just try calling the gotdx API differently from the Python client, or use `stock_kline_offset` instead, which might have a different parameter structure. Or I could look at how other methods like `stock_quotes` handle this and see if there's a pattern I can follow.\n\nWait, `stock_quotes` works fine because it passes codes and markets as strings like `\"codes\":\"000001,600519\"`. The real issue is `stock_kline` which sends numeric values. Since Go's `json.Unmarshal` into a `map[string]string` fails when it encounters a JSON number for a string field, the cleanest fix would be to write a custom `UnmarshalJSON` method on `queryRequest` that handles the conversion. Let me try that approach.","thinkingSignature":"861172e26b23f32bb1cc247df3f780d15e7ccbd488ab15fcb756384914d2829c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9itrxy1ddc0m_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\nwith open('/tmp/gotdx/cmd/webviewer/query.go', 'r') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\n# Restore all changes first\ncontent = content.replace(\n    'Params map[string]any  `json:\"params\"`',\n    'Params map[string]string `json:\"params\"`'\n)\nfor old in [\n    'func parseUint8Value(params map[string]any,',\n    'func parseUint16Value(params map[string]any,',\n    'func parseUint32Value(params map[string]any,',\n    'func parseBoolValue(params map[string]any,',\n    'func valueOrDefault(params map[string]any,',\n]:\n    content = content.replace(old, old.replace('map[string]any', 'map[string]string'))\n\nwith open('/tmp/gotdx/cmd/webviewer/query.go', 'w') as f:\n    f.write(content)\nprint(\"reverted\")\nEOF","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":37273,"output":797,"cacheRead":35206,"cacheWrite":0,"to