{"type":"message","id":"1afe804a","parentId":"a67548e1","timestamp":"2026-04-13T03:03:50.869Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - there are direct calls to `call_llm`. The task type is not currently part of the routing decision. I need to understand what task types exist and where the routing decisions happen.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The `call_llm` function takes a `provider` argument. Currently, the provider is hardcoded when calling. \n\nFor the \"task routing\" feature, I need to:\n1. Create a config that maps task types → providers\n2. Create a `route_inference(task_type, ...)` function that looks up the config and calls the right provider\n\nBut this requires changing all the call sites. A simpler approach would be:\n\n\n1. Add a new `services/inference_router.py` module with a `route(task_type, ...)` function\n2. Create `inference_routing.json` config\n3. Modify `llm_router.py` to check the routing config when provider is \"auto\"\n\nThough changing all the call sites is a big refactor. Let me look at how the llm_client is called to see if there's a more centralized entry point I'm missing.","thinkingSignature":"f0224d5a57aa7352bfe56107d38e327846f71056ae9206ca32e1b2be3201e81e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wzr69o35zkue_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"llm_client\\|def.*llm.*call\\|stage_tag\" ~/AI-RXC/services/stage1_v2/pipeline.py | grep -v \"llm_scope\\|llm_\\|#\" | head -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":61524,"output":312,"cacheRead":35206,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97042,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776049419489,"responseId":"062b900b2edd78410efe59c8d2721de8"}}
