{"type":"message","id":"3fbc24bc","parentId":"9aec0884","timestamp":"2026-04-13T09:24:45.025Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try a different approach. Instead of trying to fix all these interdependent scripts, let me write a Python script that directly generates the minimal needed files for the balanced and aggressive portfolios to have date_tag=20260413.\n\nActually, a better approach: let me just copy the 20260403 files to 20260413, as a temporary measure to make the audit pass. Then the actual fix would be to properly regenerate them when the data issues are resolved.\n\nWait, but that would be falsifying data. Not good.\n\nLet me look at this from the audit script perspective. The audit checks for:\n1. `stale_account_latest` - mtime of `paper_*_account_v1_latest.json` must be recent\n\n\n2. `stale_positions_latest` - mtime of `paper_*_portfolio_positions_latest.csv` must be recent\n3. `stale_profile_date_tag` - the dated_tag in the filenames must match today's date\n\nSo I could touch the files to update their mtime, but that doesn't fix the underlying data freshness issue. Or I could try to copy the 20260330 orders to 20260413 and regenerate from there, but I'd need to rerun the simulation with the new date which brings me back to the same blockers.\n\nThe real problem is that the prepare_paper_orders_v1 script has two issues: a daily_basic staleness check and an Arrow dtype bug. I should fix the Arrow dtype bug first and run it directly with the existing merged signals rather than going through the full auto script flow. Looking at where the error occurs in the materialize_profile_signal_chain function around line 1037, the issue happens when calling apply_stock_analysis_overlay. Let me trace through that function to see what's actually failing.","thinkingSignature":"bf28983eb3171ef427f01327dbf4e2622b1884c4f45afd385d7b3ca3346c60c0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h5ujexzksxs2_1","name":"exec","arguments"